        "title": "Guide to Hajj (Pilgrimage)",
        "body": "\n                    <p>Hajj is the fifth pillar of Islam, obligatory once in a lifetime for those physically and financially able. <em>\"And [due] to Allah from the people is a pilgrimage to the House - for whoever is able to find thereto a way.\"</em> (Quran 3:97)</p>\n                    <h4>Step-by-Step Guide (Days of Hajj)</h4>\n                    <ol>\n                        <li><strong>Preparation & Ihram (Before 8th Dhul Hijjah):</strong> Pilgrims enter a state of spiritual purity (Ihram) at the Miqat, wearing two white unstitched sheets (men) or modest clothing (women). The Talbiyah is chanted constantly.</li>\n                        <li><strong>Day 1: 8th Dhul Hijjah (Mina):</strong> Pilgrims travel to the tent city of Mina, spending the day and night in prayer, reflection, and preparation for Arafat.</li>\n                        <li><strong>Day 2: 9th Dhul Hijjah (Arafat & Muzdalifah):</strong> The climax of Hajj. Pilgrims stand on the plains of Arafat from noon till sunset, begging Allah for forgiveness (Wuquf). The Prophet ﷺ said, <em>\"Hajj is Arafat\"</em> (Tirmidhi 889). After sunset, they travel to Muzdalifah to spend the night under the stars and collect pebbles for the stoning ritual.</li>\n                        <li><strong>Day 3: 10th Dhul Hijjah (Eid al-Adha & Yawm an-Nahr):</strong> A busy day of rituals:\n                            <ul>\n                                <li><strong>Rami:</strong> Stoning the largest Jamarah (pillar) representing the devil with 7 pebbles.</li>\n                                <li><strong>Qurbani:</strong> Animal sacrifice.</li>\n                                <li><strong>Halq/Taqsir:</strong> Shaving the head (men) or trimming the hair (women) to officially leave the restricted state of Ihram.</li>\n                                <li><strong>Tawaf al-Ifadah:</strong> Returning to Mecca to circle the Ka'bah 7 times, followed by Sa'i (walking 7 times between Safa and Marwah).</li>\n                            </ul>\n                        </li>\n                        <li><strong>Days 4-6: 11th-13th Dhul Hijjah (Ayyam al-Tashreeq):</strong> Pilgrims return to Mina. On each of these days, they stone all three Jamarat (small, medium, large) with 7 pebbles each.</li>\n                        <li><strong>Farewell Tawaf (Tawaf al-Wida):</strong> Before leaving Mecca, pilgrims perform one final Tawaf around the Ka'bah, marking the end of their journey.</li>\n                    </ol>\n                    <h4>Talbiyah</h4>\n                    <div class=\"tutorial-arabic\">لَبَّيْكَ اللَّهُمَّ لَبَّيْكَ، لَبَّيْكَ لَا شَرِيكَ لَكَ لَبَّيْكَ، إِنَّ الْحَمْدَ وَالنِّعْمَةَ لَكَ وَالْمُلْكَ، لَا شَرِيكَ لَكَ</div>\n                    <div class=\"tutorial-pronunciation\">🔊 Labbayk Allahumma labbayk. Labbayk la sharika laka labbayk. Innal-hamda wan-ni'mata laka wal-mulk. La sharika lak.</div>\n                    <p>\"Here I am, O Allah, here I am. You have no partner. All praise, grace, and sovereignty are Yours.\" (Sahih Bukhari 1549)</p>\n                    <h4>Best Dua at Arafat</h4>\n                    <div class=\"tutorial-arabic\">لَا إِلَهَ إِلَّا اللَّهُ وَحْدَهُ لَا شَرِيكَ لَهُ، لَهُ الْمُلْكُ وَلَهُ الْحَمْدُ وَهُوَ عَلَى كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ</div>\n                    <div class=\"tutorial-pronunciation\">🔊 La ilaha illallahu wahdahu la sharika lah, lahul-mulku wa lahul-hamdu wa huwa 'ala kulli shay'in qadeer</div>\n                    <p>(Tirmidhi 3585)</p>\n                ",
